    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Factor<T>

    public class SaturationFactor<T>
extends IndependentFactor<T>
    Factor that selects the best active neighbor but doesn't constraint others. This is very similar to the SelectorFactor, but in this case other neighbors are allowed to be active at the same time (without an increase in utility).
    Formally, this factor is defined over a sequence of neighbors X = {x_1, ..., x_n} and a sequence of corresponding weights B = {b_1, ..., b_n}, b_i (>) 0. Then, the factor is defined as 
          f(X,B) = max_{i=1..n |Â x_i=1} b_i*x_i
    Messages are computed in O(n) time by using the derivation: 
           (v_{f->x_i} = max(b_i, b*_i) - max(-v*_i, b*_i))
    which is a simplification of the message 
           (\mu_{f->x_i}(0) = max( 0, v*_i + b*_i ))
       (\mu_{f->x_i}(1) = v*_i + max( b_i, b*_i ))
    where 
          b*   = max_i[ b_i + min(v_i, 0) ] ,
      i*   = argmax_i[ b_i + min(v_i, 0) ] ,
      b**  = max_{i != i*}[ b_i + min(v_i, 0) ] ,
      b*_i = b** if i=i*, b* otherwise ,
      v*   = \sum max(v_i, 0) ,
      v*_i = v* - max(v_i, 0) ,
    Intuitively,
    • b* is the max b value that can be achieved (penalized if the corresponding message is negative)
    • i* is the index of that best b value
    • b** is the second best b value (penalized if needed)
    • b*_i is the best (penalized) b value excluding neighbor i
    • v* is the sum of all positive messages
    • v*_i is the sum of all positive messages excluding the one from neighbor i
    Author:
    Marc Pujol (mpujol @ iiia.csic.es)
